node.text: In this episode of Building Fortunes, we look at how Elton John became one of the best-selling artists of all time. In 2020, Elton John's yearly earnings amounted to $81 million. His Farewell Yellow Brick Road Tour grossed $212 million in 2019, the second-highest tally in the business. With the pandemic postponing his North American tour dates in April, the Rocket Man will have to wait to complete his 300-show, five-continent tour.

node.text: Kendra Scott is the founder of the jewelry and lifestyle brand of the same name. She first started making jewelry out of her spare bedroom in Austin, Texas in 2002 after she couldn't find color gemstone jewelry she could afford. Her creations grew into a phenomenon, with sales north of $300 million a year and giving Scott a personal fortune worth close to a half a billion dollars. But this success was not preordained. This is the story of how Kendra Scott became one of America’s richest self-made women, and the one person who kept her dream from turning into a nightmare.

node.title: Kendra Scott's Rocky Road To Gemstone Success

node.text: In a 24-minute statement in a California courtroom, Britney Spears made it clear that she's had enough with the conservatorship that has given control of her life to her father, Jamie Spears, since 2008. Describing a litany of suffering, she pleaded with the court to gain back control of her life and put an end to the arrangement that has allowed her father to live off her career and fortune.

node.title: How Much Has Jamie Spears Earned From Britney’s $60 Million Dollar Fortune?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on July 20, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Forbes Jeff Bezos Successfully Launches On Blue Origin's First Crewed Spaceflight'.

node.text: On Tuesday at 8:12 am CDT, a Blue Origin New Shepard spacecraft launched a space capsule, the RSS First Step and its crew on a suborbital jaunt that mimicked the same type of flight made by American astronaut Alan Shepherd 60 years ago. Among that crew was company founder Jeff Bezos, taking his own small step 21 years after getting his space company started. “I want to go on this flight because it’s a thing I’ve wanted to do all my life,” Bezos said in a video broadcast before the launch. He was joined by his brother, Mark, customer Oliver Daemon and 82-year-old aviation pioneer Wally Funk. Since its founding in 2000, Bezos has held Blue Origin to himself. He’s put an estimated $7.5 billion of his own money into the company, and unlike rival billionaires Richard Branson or Elon Musk, has taken no venture funding or other investment. Blue Origin’s space development has been slow and steady, which is a specific design philosophy: the company’s motto is “Gradatim ferociter,” which translates to “step-by-step ferociously,” and its mascot is a tortoise, a reference to the famous Aesop fable. It flew its first test vehicle in 2005, and its first rocket in 2006. But it wasn’t until 2012 that it flew the first test of its New Shepard suborbital spaceflight system, which was a test of the company’s pad escape system. Tap the link in bio for the full read. (📸: AFP via Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on July 19, 2021. May be an image of 9 people and text that says 'How To Copy Your Business Rival's Idea And Get Away With It Forbes'.

node.text: Over the last year or so, Twitter carried out an act of high-tech petty larceny: swiping what originally was Snapchat’s idea for a Stories function, where users publish ephemeral content to all their followers, and adding it to its app. Twitter called its version “Fleets,” since, well, the photos, text and video there enjoyed only fleeting existences. This sort of theft is commonplace in Silicon Valley, and unless a business wants to lock horns with an opponent in a costly legal battle, there’s not much to do about it—except hope the copycat ends up meeting the same end as Fleets did. Yep, the feature’s a goner. Twitter said last week it would remove Fleets on August 3, less than a year after making it widely available to users. Plenty of other copycat products have perished, struggled or plain fizzled out in similar fashion. There’s a right way to produce a successful knockoff, and, as Twitter and these others have found, a wrong way, too. Probably the most obvious example of a successful bit of technological pilfering is what Instagram did with Stories back in 2016. By 2018, Instagram Stories had nearly 400 million daily users, while Snapchat’s growth had largely plateaued at half that figure. Tap the link in bio for the full read on how Instagram was successful. (📸: Getty Images)

node.text: Canada will ease border restrictions to fully vaccinated travelers from the United States starting Aug. 9, the country’s government announced Monday, despite no concrete plans from its neighbors on when long-standing travel restrictions will be lifted in return. Starting in August, fully vaccinated U.S. citizens and permanent residents living in the U.S. will be allowed to enter Canada for non-essential travel, according to a statement released by the government. This marks the first time in nearly 16 months Americans will be allowed to enter Canada for anything other than essential travel. The country will then open up to international travelers beginning Sept. 7, the government said, provided that the “Covid-19 epidemiology remains favorable.” Tap the link in bio for more details. (📸: Getty Images)

node.text: In April 2017, Press Secretary Sean Spicer took the podium in the White House briefing room and announced that the president was donating his first-quarter salary to the National Park Service. With a serious look on his face, Spicer pulled out an oversized check with an oversized signature. It was the first of several checks that Donald Trump signed while in office, handing over his $400,000 salary in exchange for good publicity. That was pocket change for Trump. His real money came from the business he refused to divest, not from his government salary. An analysis of documents, some of which only became public in recent weeks, shows just how much Trump’s businesses raked in while he was in office. Dig through everything—including property records, ethics disclosures, debt documents and securities filings—and you’ll find about $2.4 billion of revenue from January 2017 to December 2020. If not for the pandemic, there would have been even more. Forbes estimates the pandemic helped wipe about $200 million off Trump’s top line last year. Tap the link in bio for the full read. (📸: Jamel Toppin for Forbes)

node.text: Billions of viewers. The moral support of nations. Weeks of gushing coverage from media outlets around the world. Olympic glory is a heady dream-come-true for almost every athlete who makes it, but few are doing it for the money, and it's certainly no easy way to get rich. Paying for trainers, facility time and state-of-the-art equipment that can cost tens of thousands of dollars can turn the chance to compete on the world stage into a money pit. For some, the cost of a trip to the Olympics can be so high that they turn to GoFundMe campaigns to help pay their way. Winning helps defray some of the costs, with each U.S. gold medalist bringing home $37,500, silver medalists $22,500 and bronze $15,000. But most fall short. However, thanks to a decision made decades ago that allows professional athletes to compete, this year’s Games will once again host not just struggling hopefuls but also some of the world’s top-paid athletes. Among the top earners set to be in Tokyo: three professional tennis players, a golfer and five NBA players. Tap the link in bio to see the nine highest-earning Olympians headed to Tokyo, who together made a combined $353 million in the past year.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on July 18, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Forbes A How Covid Affected Employee Perks And What They Will Look Like Post-Pandemic'.

node.text: Businesses are substituting employee perks like free in-office lunches and stocked fridges for subscriptions to mental health apps, working from home stipends and now, even Peloton memberships. The exercise equipment company recently launched a corporate wellness program that allows employers to offer workers subsidized access to Peloton’s digital fitness membership, its cycles and treadmills. The Covid-19 pandemic forced many employers to rethink how they use perks to engage and reward their workers. Flexibility, once a selling point, became the norm overnight. Those snack-filled pantries lay empty. But now the debate around employee perks mirrors many of the conversations around how people are likely to work when the pandemic is over. Peloton's announcement, for one, is a sign that many employers believe some form of remote working is here to stay. Out of all the new benefits, the one provided most frequently is a stipend or reimbursement for work-at-home office equipment, with 60% of companies offering this, according to Robert Half. In addition to stipends, Pringle is seeing employers increase vacation time and paid time off for workers. Tap the link in bio for the full read. (📸: Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on July 18, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, outdoors and text that says 'Google Just Unlocked The Mysteries OfTravel Demand- And The Tourism Industry Can't Wait To Have At It'.

node.text: For a great many of the 16 million people who work in the $2.6 trillion U.S. tourism industry, getting an accurate assessment of travel demand is akin to finding the Holy Grail. For destination organizations and visitor bureaus at the national, state and local level, pinning down where people want to travel is the key to efficiently managing budgets and spending. Airlines gauge travel demand when deciding where to open new routes. Hotels and other tourism-related businesses use demand forecasting to right-size supply and determine how many employees to hire. But predicting travel demand has become harder over the past decade, and the Covid-19 pandemic has upended traditional forecasting models that rely on recent historical data. To help, earlier this week Google launched Travel Insights with Google, a brand new suite of free tools that leverage Google Search data to deliver insights into real-time travel demand. The first tool, Destination Insights, gives travel businesses, governments and tourism boards a clear picture of where travel demand is coming from so they can plan accordingly. A second tool, Hotel Insights, has been customized to help hoteliers analyze search trends so they can attract new guests based on where interest is coming from. Tap the link in bio for how this may impact the tourism industry. (📸: Getty Images)

node.text: Meghan Markle is developing an animated series for Netflix that will tell the stories of influential women by blending adventure, fantasy and history, her and husband Prince Harry’s production company Archewell announced Wednesday. With a working title of 'Pearl,' a Netflix statement described the project as a “family series” that follows a 12-year-old girl as she embarks on an adventure and meets important women from throughout history along the way. “Like many girls her age, our heroine Pearl is on a journey of self-discovery as she tries to overcome life’s daily challenges,” Markle said in a statement. Markle will work as creator and executive producer on the project. 'Pearl' is the second Archewell Production project announced for Netflix, part of the Sussexes’ $100 million contract with the streaming giant signed last year. Tap the link in bio to learn more. (📸: Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on July 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing and text that says 'Forbes Here's Why A 40-Year-Old Queen Album Has Taken Over The Charts'.

node.text: In an era where streaming dominates and the latest trends start on TikTok, the classic '70s rock band Queen is having a renewed run on the charts the old-fashioned way—through selling CDs, cassettes and vinyl records. Queen’s 'Greatest Hits,' containing tracks like "Bohemian Rhapsody" and "We Are the Champions," came in at No. 3 on this past week’s U.S.-based Billboard “Top Album Sales” chart. The album is performing even better in the band’s native U.K., where it came in as the No. 2 album on the Official Charts Co. listing last week—just 270 sales short of Olivia Rodrigo’s 'Sour,' which tops both the U.S. and U.K. album sales charts. Its jump in popularity comes after a 40th anniversary re-release of the album on July 2, with 2021 also serving as the 50th anniversary of the original band’s formation. The re-release has sparked a run on physical copies, which make up the vast majority of sales. According to the Official Charts Co., 78% of sales last week came from either CD, cassette or vinyl. Tap the link in bio for more info. (📸: WireImage)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Forbes on July 17, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'How To Conjure A $20 Billion Fortune Using A SPAC Forbes'.

node.text: The new high watermark in financial alchemy using special purpose acquisition corporations, or SPACs, was unlocked this past week with a deal that aims to conjure tens of billions of dollars almost entirely out of thin air. On Monday morning, a SPAC called Lionheart Acquisition Corp. II unveiled a deal to take a firm that pursues Medicare litigation, called MSP Recovery, public at a whopping $32.6 billion enterprise value. The SPAC says it values MSP at about 10.5-times expected 2023 revenues. If the deal goes through, and the market agrees with Lionheart’s valuation, it would make founder and CEO John Ruiz’s estimated 70% stake worth over $20 billion, while his partner Frank Quesada’s estimated 24% stake would be around $7 billion—on paper at least. But here’s the rub. It’s all projections and hopes and dreams. The SPAC deal relies on heady estimates of what its claims are potentially worth, and its entire income statement is hypothetical in nature. In fact, MSP will generate precisely $0 in revenues this year, according to its own projections. Tap the link in bio for the full read. (📸: AP)
